<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Draw" class="currentChild" href="Draw">Draw</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
To generate an illustration or illustration vector either manually (using pen and ink on a substrate) or digitally (using a <a title="drawing program" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/drawing_program">drawing program</a>). 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In <a title="Binding and Finishing" href="Binding_and_Finishing">binding and finishing</a>, the term <em>draw</em> refers to the gathered sections (or <a title="Signature" href="Signature">signature</a>s) of a book. Depending upon the number of signatures vs. the number of stations on the <a title="Gathering" href="Gathering">gathering</a> machine, book sections may need to be assembled in more than one stage. A <a title="Double Draw" href="Double_Draw">double draw</a> is two batches of sections that are assembled, while a <a title="Triple Draw" href="Triple_Draw">triple draw</a> is three batches to assemble. 
</p>
<p id="l5">
In <a title="Cutting and Trimming" href="Cutting_and_Trimming">cutting and trimming</a>, the term <em>draw</em> also refers to any dragging motion of a cutting knife. 
</p>
